We don't know which family the virus comes from, but  CoV(coronavirus) is most likely, and human to human transmission is guaranteed by those numbers. Since it infects the breathing system, it's spread by aerosol, which is bad. It's fast and efficient. One sneeze in an airport...

We'll see what variant of coronavirus we're dealing with soon, I hope. I can't believe the sequence still isn't out.  Surely there's been a gain of function or important mutation, or it is indeed plain SARS and they don't want to freak out Chinese people.  My bet's on the latter.

That, and it depends on how efficiently and how far this spreads.  Given how fast coronavirus mutates and recombinates, we could be dealing with a virus that is very different from SARS.  SARS apparently had an R0 of 2-4, which is very high.

If any virus is going to mutate, it's a coronavirus. Both an unstable genome(I forget how many base pairs per generation) and the unique ability to recombinate(hence labeling by antigens, like H3N2, etc.

I can confirm from inside information that this is not a known coronavirus, adenovirus, or avian flu.  That doesn't rule out other recombinants or mutations of the flu, but it makes it unlikely.  Probably a coronavirus.
